They are a husband and wife
team of treasure hunters

01:44.958 --> 01:48.583
who claim to have uncovered
new and surprising information

01:48.708 --> 01:52.333
surrounding a long-lost shipment
of Civil War-era gold

01:52.500 --> 01:53.833
that is believed
to lie somewhere

01:53.958 --> 01:55.250
at the bottom of Lake Michigan,

01:55.375 --> 01:59.250
near the shores of
the area's famed Poverty Island.

01:59.375 --> 02:01.667
MATTY:
This story alone,

02:01.833 --> 02:04.083
the estimates are there's
$400 million dollars' worth

02:04.208 --> 02:07.500
of Civil War gold
still in Lake Michigan,

02:07.667 --> 02:10.083
-somewhere around
Poverty Island.
-Yep.

02:11.208 --> 02:13.333
NARRATOR:
In 1863,

02:13.417 --> 02:16.500
at the height of
the American Civil War,

02:16.583 --> 02:19.333
the Union Navy's blockade
of Southern seaports

02:19.458 --> 02:22.208
had cut off Confederate
shipments of cotton to Europe,

02:22.375 --> 02:24.333
devastating the French economy.

02:24.458 --> 02:29.625
In response, France's emperor
Napoleon Bonaparte III,

02:29.708 --> 02:32.958
nephew of Napoleon I,
reportedly came up

02:33.083 --> 02:35.167
with a daring plan to smuggle

02:35.250 --> 02:37.500
over $4.5 million dollars'
worth of gold

02:37.583 --> 02:39.333
into the hands
of the Confederacy

02:39.417 --> 02:41.042
to help them win the war.

02:41.167 --> 02:42.708
In the early days,

02:42.833 --> 02:44.833
the Great Lakes were highways.

02:45.000 --> 02:46.833
They were water-based highways.

02:46.958 --> 02:49.500
Europeans came through

02:49.625 --> 02:52.458
what we know today
as the St. Lawrence Seaway,

02:52.542 --> 02:56.167
a passageway leading
from the Atlantic Ocean

02:56.292 --> 02:58.292
into Lake Ontario.

02:58.417 --> 03:00.375
And then that connects
to Lake Erie

03:00.542 --> 03:03.500
and Huron
and Superior and Michigan.

03:03.625 --> 03:06.458
So, this was truly
a highway system.

03:06.542 --> 03:09.000
NARRATOR:
But when the ship
carrying the gold

03:09.125 --> 03:10.583
made its way onto Lake Michigan,

03:10.708 --> 03:13.250
it was spotted
by a Union vessel,

03:13.375 --> 03:15.292
which then began to give chase.

03:15.417 --> 03:18.375
Fearful of being overtaken

03:18.542 --> 03:21.125
and having this valuable
shipment fall into enemy hands,

03:21.250 --> 03:22.750
the French captain gave an order

03:22.875 --> 03:25.833
for the boxes of gold
to be chained together

03:26.000 --> 03:27.792
and thrown overboard.

03:27.875 --> 03:29.333
WESTRICK:
The reason you'd chain
all these boxes together

03:29.417 --> 03:31.375
would be to retrieve them later.

03:31.542 --> 03:34.167
If it's chained together, you're
gonna be able to drag a hook,

03:34.333 --> 03:35.958
grappling anchor
through the area

03:36.083 --> 03:37.542
and snag it and retrieve them.

03:37.667 --> 03:40.458
NARRATOR:
However, according to legend,

03:40.542 --> 03:43.292
the French ship was sunk
shortly after

03:43.375 --> 03:46.333
scuttling its cargo,
and both it and the gold

03:46.500 --> 03:49.500
were lost beneath
the waters of Lake Michigan.

03:49.667 --> 03:54.667
Until, as some accounts state,
the year 1933,

03:54.833 --> 03:58.333
when a Milwaukee-based treasure
hunter named Wilfred Behrens,

03:58.417 --> 04:01.042
leading a search operation
aboard his ship

04:01.167 --> 04:03.292
the <i>Captain Lawrence,</i>

04:03.375 --> 04:05.000
reportedly located
the sunken chests

04:05.167 --> 04:08.000
using a diving bell drag line

04:08.125 --> 04:09.792
just offshore
from Poverty Island.

04:09.917 --> 04:12.958
The operation was witnessed
by an 11-year-old

04:13.042 --> 04:17.542
named Karly Jessen, the son of
the island's lighthouse keeper.

04:17.667 --> 04:21.167
WESTRICK:
The young son would
sit on the shore watching

04:21.250 --> 04:22.917
the <i>Captain Lawrence,</i>
watching the diving bell,

04:23.042 --> 04:25.042
watching the operations,

04:25.167 --> 04:27.333
and something unusual
happened on board.

04:27.458 --> 04:29.167
They were out there
hooting and hollering.

04:29.292 --> 04:31.042
The lighthouse keeper's son,

04:31.208 --> 04:32.833
he thought they had
discovered something.

04:32.958 --> 04:36.458
NARRATOR:
But just after
Wilfred Behrens and his crew

04:36.583 --> 04:38.917
were reported to have made
their astonishing discovery,

04:39.042 --> 04:40.958
a violent storm rolled in.

04:41.042 --> 04:43.292
Both the <i>Captain Lawrence</i>

04:43.417 --> 04:45.667
and anything it may have
taken on board

04:45.792 --> 04:48.500
were quickly lost
beneath the waves.

04:50.542 --> 04:52.417
RICK:
I think there's reason
to be very hopeful.

04:52.542 --> 04:55.542
I'm so glad I'm getting
another crack at this,

04:55.708 --> 04:57.875
