16:18.167 --> 16:19.583
MATTY:
Boy, yeah.

16:19.708 --> 16:21.792
I think if we run lines
back and forth here.

16:21.875 --> 16:23.125
Mow the lawn, as they say.

16:23.250 --> 16:24.375
Yeah, mow the lawn.

16:24.500 --> 16:26.500
MATTY:
All right, let's do it.

16:26.625 --> 16:27.667
GROLEAU:
How are we looking, Todd,
are we up and running?

16:27.833 --> 16:29.167
Ready to start scanning?

16:29.292 --> 16:31.042
-We are set to go.
-GROLEAU: All right.

16:31.875 --> 16:33.583
NARRATOR:
Today,

16:33.708 --> 16:35.583
the team will be using

16:35.708 --> 16:40.917
the Garmin ECHOMAP UHD
93SV side-scan sonar device.

16:41.042 --> 16:43.917
As the team's search vessel
moves back and forth

16:44.042 --> 16:46.417
in a grid pattern
across the lake's surface,

16:46.542 --> 16:49.375
the device will emit
pulses of sound waves

16:49.542 --> 16:52.250
pointed down
toward the lake bottom.

16:52.375 --> 16:55.667
The acoustic reflections
that are subsequently generated

16:55.792 --> 16:59.167
help to form three-dimensional
images of any objects

16:59.250 --> 17:02.667
or structures
that might be located below.

17:04.083 --> 17:06.333
MATTY:
What are some little tells
that you see sometimes where

17:06.417 --> 17:07.500
there's something, you go,
"Okay, that's clearly...":

17:07.625 --> 17:08.875
You know, do you see like,

17:09.042 --> 17:10.000
raised feature
or something like that

17:10.083 --> 17:11.625
-when you know?
-Yeah, especially

17:11.750 --> 17:13.000
if you go right over,
because you'll see it

17:13.125 --> 17:14.042
on both sides in the black area.

17:14.167 --> 17:16.083
Right, right.

17:16.208 --> 17:17.583
GROLEAU:
A lot of times you see
shadows, too,

17:17.708 --> 17:18.667
the taller the object,

17:18.833 --> 17:20.333
you'll see a shadow.

17:20.500 --> 17:22.125
-It'll be casting a shadow?
-Yeah, exactly.

17:22.208 --> 17:23.500
Just like shining
a light on something.

17:23.625 --> 17:24.583
MATTY:
Sure.

17:28.250 --> 17:31.250
TODD:
Ah, there's something
interesting.

17:31.375 --> 17:33.000
GROLEAU:
What do we got there?

17:33.167 --> 17:34.583
I think that's our shipwreck.

17:34.708 --> 17:36.375
Coming right up the wreck.

17:36.500 --> 17:37.958
MATTY:
Yeah, you can totally see that.

17:38.042 --> 17:39.792
So we're right on it right now.

17:39.875 --> 17:42.167
GROLEAU:
Right over the top of it.

17:43.042 --> 17:45.000
MATTY:
Boom. That's so cool!

17:45.083 --> 17:47.500
This is extending up to
150 feet to starboard.

17:47.625 --> 17:49.542
-Holy moly.
-Yeah.

17:49.667 --> 17:52.333
MATTY:
And what do we know about
the dimensions of that boat?

17:53.250 --> 17:55.333
-It's in the ballpark, yeah.
-All right, good.

17:56.333 --> 17:58.458
You're absolutely in
the ballpark, that's a wreck.

18:00.667 --> 18:02.875
-JESS: What's that?
-GROLEAU: Yeah, what's that?

18:03.042 --> 18:05.042
What's that?

18:05.208 --> 18:07.083
-GROLEAU: That's pronounced.
-MATTY: Yeah.

18:07.208 --> 18:09.167
GROLEAU:
We got something else there.

18:09.250 --> 18:11.083
JESS:
What is that?

18:15.167 --> 18:17.500
-JESS: What's that?
-GROLEAU: Yeah, what's that?

18:17.667 --> 18:19.208
-There's something.
-What's that?

18:19.917 --> 18:21.333
NARRATOR:
In Lake Michigan,

18:21.458 --> 18:23.333
just off the coast
of Poverty Island,

18:23.417 --> 18:26.375
while investigating
a shipwreck believed

18:26.542 --> 18:30.667
to possibly contain $400 million
in lost Civil War gold,

18:30.833 --> 18:32.750
Rick Lagina and the team

18:32.875 --> 18:35.333
have just made what could be
a surprising discovery.

18:35.458 --> 18:37.792
I haven't seen that before.

18:39.375 --> 18:40.667
GROLEAU:
We got something else there,

18:40.750 --> 18:42.000
possibly two wrecks.

18:42.083 --> 18:43.292
One across the top of another.

18:43.417 --> 18:45.667
It does, it looks like two.

18:45.750 --> 18:48.083
MATTY:
Right now, I'm following
the imaging on the screen,

18:48.208 --> 18:50.292
and we see what clearly
could be a ship

18:50.375 --> 18:51.333
and then, all of a sudden,

18:51.458 --> 18:53.333
we all kind of realize

18:53.458 --> 18:55.250
that there could be two.

18:55.375 --> 18:59.333
GROLEAU:
So we got one shipwreck this way
and another one

18:59.458 --> 19:01.333
-laying across it.
-MATTY: Holy moly.

19:01.417 --> 19:03.375
-So you got one here...
-Wow!

19:03.542 --> 19:05.125
...and the other one across it.

19:06.667 --> 19:09.000
RICK:
And that would fit
the story, right?

19:09.167 --> 19:10.917
It definitely fits the story.

19:11.042 --> 19:12.208
MATTY:
(claps) Come on!

19:12.375 --> 19:14.708
-Come on, this is great!
-Well done.

19:14.833 --> 19:18.375
MATTY:
This is one of those
awesome times when what

19:18.500 --> 19:20.583
you're finding fits the story.

19:20.708 --> 19:23.958
And the story here is
that a ship sank

19:24.083 --> 19:27.167
after they jettisoned
Civil War gold

19:27.250 --> 19:28.917
into Lake Michigan.

19:29.042 --> 19:31.083
Another ship,
at a later date, came,

19:31.208 --> 19:33.500
possibly found some of
that gold, but then sank.

19:33.667 --> 19:36.458
And so, we are finding
evidence of two ships.

19:36.542 --> 19:39.417
One looks like it could possibly
be on top of the other.

19:39.542 --> 19:41.917
That fits the story,
so that's exciting.

19:42.042 --> 19:43.917
That's two ships.

19:44.042 --> 19:47.708
And if one went down,
and there was already one down,

19:47.833 --> 19:50.250
it would pretty much, could look
like that right, Mike?

19:50.375 --> 19:52.167
That's what I would
expect it to look like.

19:52.333 --> 19:54.292
-I love it.
-That's awesome.

19:54.375 --> 19:56.292
How you feeling,
Jess, right now?

19:56.417 --> 19:58.500
Pretty awesome. I'm, like,
I'm speechless, for once.

19:58.667 --> 20:00.167
MATTY:
Your hard work's paying off.

