24:15.625 --> 24:17.792
NARRATOR:
Ballast stones?

24:17.917 --> 24:20.208
Lying adjacent
to the wooden remains of

24:20.375 --> 24:22.000
a shipwreck on the lake floor?

24:23.583 --> 24:26.375
During the 18th
and 19th centuries,

24:26.542 --> 24:28.875
ballast stones were
commonly placed

24:29.042 --> 24:31.125
in the hulls of
large sailing vessels

24:31.208 --> 24:33.958
to offer additional
weight and stability to ships

24:34.083 --> 24:37.500
as they traveled over
rough or unstable waters.

24:37.667 --> 24:39.958
Could these
ballast stones suggest

24:40.042 --> 24:42.583
that the shipwreck
the team has just found

24:42.708 --> 24:45.458
might date as far back
as the Civil War?

24:46.500 --> 24:48.458
If so, might it be the ship

24:48.542 --> 24:50.833
that once carried
the lost cache of gold

24:50.958 --> 24:52.667
that the <i>Captain Lawrence</i>
and its crew

24:52.833 --> 24:56.458
were reported
to have found in 1933,

24:56.583 --> 24:59.750
before also sinking
to the bottom of the lake?

24:59.875 --> 25:02.167
The ballast stones are key
in a lot of ways,

25:02.292 --> 25:03.667
because, first of all,
it narrows

25:03.750 --> 25:05.667
what kind of ship
it could be,

25:05.792 --> 25:09.167
and when that ship was sailing.

25:32.208 --> 25:33.042
MATTY:
Oh, Rick!

